The Swastika is one of the oldest symbols known to Humankind. The word Swastika, स्वस्तिक, comes from the Sanskrit words su + asti = well + being (सु + अस्ति = स्वस्ति) or all be well.

Theories of single origin as a sacred prehistorical symbol point to the Proto-Indo-Europeans, noting that the Swastika was not adopted by the Sumerians in Mesopotamia.

The Swastika has been used in the civilizations of the East for over 10,000 years and is considered highly sacred by Buddhists, Hindus, Jains and Zoroastrians.

In the Near East, the Swastika has been in use since the times of Assyria and Babylon, 5,000 years ago, and made its way down to Africa where it has been found in excavations across Egyptian sites and on pottery in the area of the Kushite heartland.

The Swastika began to appear in the Neolithic Vinca culture across South-Eastern Europe around 8,000 years ago and had become widespread across the whole continent of Europe by the Bronze Age.

In the Americas, the Swastika appears in the artwork of various Native American tribes and was used by Mesoamerican cultures including the Aztecs, Incas and Mayans.

The oldest discovered artifact to depict a Swastika is a 15,000 year old small ivory figurine of a female bird, carved out of a mammoth tusk, with an intricate meander pattern of joined up Swastikas engraved on the torso. Located at the National Museum of the History of Ukraine in Kiev, it was found in 1908 at the Paleolithic settlement of Mezin near the Russian border. The bird was found with a number of phallic objects which supports the idea that the Swastika pattern was used as a fertility symbol.

Perhaps the origin of the Swastika pattern resides in the star systems observed by our ancient ancestors. The Big Dipper constellation, when viewed relative to the position of the North Star during the four seasons, forms the appearance of the Swastika.
